column17: Metric that measures the potency of a cell
Measures rate of change of a cell (in the context of shifting towards neighbouring cell states)
Cells from organoids with first cancer hit (Knock-down of the Apc gene). Cells with just a hit on A should not be considered cancerous just yet.
Cells from organoids with second cancer hit (cancer causing mutation of Kras gene). Cells with both K and P hits could be considered cancerous
Cells from organoids with the third cancer hit (disables the cancer inhibiting P53 gene).  Cells with both K and P hits could be considered cancerous.
Cells from organoids grown with a coctail of growth promoting chemicals, which mimick in some ways both what cancer does but also what the fibroblasts do to the organoids
Cells from organoids grown together with macrophages
Cells from organoids grown together with fibroblasts (this cell type changes the structure of the growth media and also secretes a lot of chemicals that the organoids pick up)

Annotations on the different cell states of the organoid. They form a sort of developmental continuum, with the Enterocytes and Goblet/DCS states being on one end, and the 3 CSC (stem cells) states being on the other)
Score that determines how well a cell matches a signature describing the proliferative stem cells (one of the stem cell states of interest, associated with cancer)
Score that determines how well a cell matches a signature describing the revival stem cells (one of the stem cell states of interest, associated with signalling from fibroblasts)
